These photos are great to demonstrate some keys to hitting a topspin backhand. Many players struggle with topspin. The first image shows how extreme Nadal drops that racket head on the backhand. The lower the racket drops the more spin you can create. Most people just don’t get under the ball enough with the racket head.

Denis Shapovalov service coil 

If you struggle to coil your body in your service delivery, changing the positioning of your back foot can significantly improve your ability to do so. 

You don’t have to be as extreme as Denise but you can certainly play around with where you like that foot to be and what feels comfortable.

If your forehand technique breaks down on floaters and moon balls consider taking a look at how you use your off hand and when you release it from the racket. 

The off hand plays a crucial role in preparing and storing energy for release in the unit turn. 
If yours comes off too early it can lead to the stroke breaking down and resorting to pushing back. 🙅🏻‍♂️

2 general rules for poaching 🎯 

🎯 The net players feet on a high ball
🎯 the baseliners side with an angle on the low ball

✅ the higher your contact point on the volley
✅ the more angle you can create 
✅ the easier it is to volley down on your opponents at the net

The SABR (Sneak Attack By Roger)

Great shock tactic against a second serve to pressure the server into immediate defense after a 2nd serve. 

Especially useful when there is plenty of scoreboard pressure on your opponent and you can afford to lose the point if it’s unsuccessful (eg 0-40, 15-40).

✅chiP n charge
✅ rip n charge 
✅ SABR
✅ Drop and charge 

Are all examples of return approaches you can practice.

How high should your ball toss be? 🤔 

This data from @uspta master pro James R Shaughnessy goes deep on both ATP/WTA tour pros ball toss height from peak ⬆️ to contact 💥 

He found that the majority of Grand Slam winners had a peak to contact drop of no more than 20 inches. 

Tossing higher can often lead to players having more timing issues as the ball has greater downward velocity due to the additional gravity. 

If you have timing issues on the serve have a look at how high your ball toss is in relation to your contact point. 

Hope this helps.

Use your off hand to prepare your overhead/smash 🤚🏼✅ 

Look around at amateur tennis players all over the world and as soon as the lob goes up they separate their hands to point the non racket hand at the ball. 

Keeping the non racket hand on the racket helps you to prepare the racket properly, turn the upper body and get into a position to unwind and swing up to the overhead more effectively. 

This should be a shot everyone loves to hit rather than one you dread.

Kei Nishikori’s return routine 🎾 @keinishikori 👈🏼

Out of the staggered stance Nishikori times his initial step with the opponents ball toss to create his forward momentum into the return. 

He can create more or less forward momentum depending on the explosiveness and size of the lead step. 

He will also use this lead step to create angles of approach for the split step to bait and cover targets for his opponent. 🧠 🎯

3 keys for the Tsonga Slice Backhand 🔑 🎾 @tsongaofficiel 👈🏼

✅ early and aggressive preparation. Racket is up near the off shoulder. 

✅ left hand assists in keeping the body side on through contact. This allows the racket to track out away from the body. 

✅ contact angle! A good low slice racket face Only open around 10 degrees. It’s a lot flatter at contact than many people think.

📝 sometimes to work on the contact angle I like to have the player try and stop the racket at contact and keep a really short follow through. Really helps them to feel and correct the angle of the racket face

Andrey Rublev has an amazing forehand. His racket head speed on the forehand is facilitated by the preparation. 👆🏼💣 🎾 @andreyrublev

Don’t get me wrong, Rublev has a solid backhand. He’s one of the best players in the world. BUT when you look at the BEST backhands, the commonality is the racket head is up ⬆️ in the unit turn. 🔑 

Preparing the racket head up in the unit turn is a big key to racket head speed and disguise when you wish to hit a slice.

✅ Attacking a players forehand on their second serve is a great option. 🧠 🎾 

Especially against players with big forehands who are typically used to defending with their backhands. Over time they get really good at doing this! Usually the backhand is more compact and they don’t take as much risk. 

When you go strong to the opponents forehand instead you can have great success for the following reasons. 👇🏼

✅ surprise 
✅ hitting a defensive forehand is not the same as an offensive forehand 
✅ you open up their backhand for the next ball
✅ your opponent will start to recover more neutral after a second serve making it easier to attack the backhand again if you choose to

Having a look at the Andy Roddick slice serve down the “T” to the AD side ☄️ 🎾 

Typically when we think of slice serves to the AD side we think of a lefty pulling the Returner out wide and off the court. A devastating serve for a lefty and one of the big advantages they have since 75% of game points are started in the AD COURT if you are playing standard scoring. 

HOWEVER 👇🏼

Right handers can also use the slice serve to the AD COURT to great effect by using their slice serve to break away from the returner, force them on the stretch in the middle of the court and go to work from there. 💪🏼

The key is really how much movement (side spin/slice) can you create. Most players go for the bomb down the T and the ball travels straight at an angle that’s easier to track down for the returner. 🌪 

✅My favorite drill for this is very simple.👇🏼
Place a cone on the hash mark on the baseline and serve T trying to make the second bounce land on the left of the target. 

Work on your swing T and you will ad a very dangerous tool in your bag. 🧰

Having a look at the Andy Roddick slice serve down the “T” to the AD side ☄️ 🎾 

Typically when we think of slice serves to the AD side we think of a lefty pulling the Returner out wide and off the court. A devastating serve for a lefty and one of the big advantages they have since 75% of game points are started in the AD COURT if you are playing standard scoring. 

HOWEVER 👇🏼

Right handers can also use the slice serve to the AD COURT to great effect by using their slice serve to break away from the returner, force them on the stretch in the middle of the court and go to work from there. 💪🏼

The key is really how much movement (side spin/slice) can you create. Most players go for the bomb down the T and the ball travels straight at an angle that’s easier to track down for the returner. 🌪 

✅My favorite drill for this is very simple.👇🏼
Place a cone on the hash mark on the baseline and serve T trying to make the second bounce land on the left of the target. 

Work on your swing T and you will ad a very dangerous tool in your bag. 🧰

Distance to contact 

Many players struggle with the timing of their strokes. Good players adjust the size of their backswing to make sure they make optimum contact. That’s the MOST important aspect of any stroke. 

If your backswing is not efficient it can really work against you in lots of different areas. 
* Hitting late 
* Backing up off the baseline to fit your swing in 
* Struggling to approach the net 
* Missing returns 
* Missing volleys 
Are just some examples

Become focused on timing your contact point and play cleaner more efficient tennis

Backhand Volley 

Learning a backhand volley can be tough. 
I’ve found that training a two handed volley with the off hand on the throat (instead of the grip) has some huge benefits 

✅ naturally keeps the racket head above the wrist 
✅ harder to develop bad habits like swinging or chopping 
✅ encourages shoulder turn 
✅ requires better movement to get to the ball since reach is limited
✅ much easier transition to a 1 handed volley where the off hand is in the same position

this is often where inefficiencies start in a players stroke. You must have a disciplined ready position AND a CLEAN and repeatable transition through the unit turn to prepare the stroke.

Second serve type and neutralizing your opponent

Second serves are often where we first come under attack on our serve. An underrated way to neutralize your opponent is to find the type of serve that they least prefer and use that. 

For some players, it might be the slice serve which you can hit harder and force the opponent into a lower contact point. For others it might be a kick. Serve you can get up high on their weaker wing. 

Pay attention in your matches to the type of serves your opponent least prefers and consider using that more often on your second.

Drop shot approach 💡 🎾 

Using her drop shot as an approach is a great way to bring your opponent forward at a disadvantage and take control of the net. 

Many players look for the drop shot as an outright winner and often under hit the shot. Treating it as an approach option means you will put more in play and take away more of the court from your opponent if they get to the ball. 

📝 A drop shot is best use an a secondary play. The success of this shot is typically dependent on both your and your opponents court positioning and the disguise before the shot.
